<h2>Repetitiveness â‰ˆ compressibility?</h2>

<p>
You may not have heard of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LZ77_and_LZ78">Lempel-Ziv algorithm</a>, but you probably use it every day. It's a lossless compression algorithm that powers gifs, pngs, and most archive formats (zip, gzip, rar...).
</p>

<p>
What does this have to do with pop music? The Lempel-Ziv algorithm works by exploiting repeated sequences. How efficiently LZ can compress a text is directly correlated with the number and length of the repeated sections in that text.
</p>

<p>In short, the LZ algorithm scans the input from start to end looking for sections that match an earlier part of the text. If it finds one then, in the output, it replaces that repeated text with a signpost that says "go back X letters, and copy Y characters".
</p>

<p>It's probably easier to understand when seen in action. Let's see what the LZ algorithm does to Lady Gaga's <i>Bad Romance</i>...
